Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 8 servings) and preheat
oven to 425 degrees.

Wash and dry produce.

Halve @bell peppers{4} lengthwise; remove stems and seeds. Halve, peel, and dice
@yellow onion{1} into ¼-inch pieces.

Place bell pepper halves on a #baking sheet{} (divide between two baking sheets
for 8 servings) and drizzle each half with @cooking oil{2%tsp}; rub to coat.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Arrange cut sides down on sheet. Roast on top rack (top and middle racks for 8)
until tender, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
@ground beef{20%ounce}, onion, half the @Italian seasoning{1%tbsp} (you'll use
the rest in the next step), one packet of @chicken stock concentrate{1} (two
packets for 8 servings), salt, and pepper. (For 8, cook in batches or use a
second large pan.)

Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through,
~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat. Using a #slotted spoon{}, transfer beef mixture
to a #large bowl{}. (TIP: If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it
out.) Wipe out pan.

While beef cooks, peel and mince or grate @garlic{3%cloves}. Roughly chop
@parsley{1/4%ounce}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add garlic and cook,
stirring, until fragrant, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Stir in @crushed tomatoes{13.76%ounce}, remaining Italian seasoning,
remaining @chicken stock concentrate{2}(used in previous step),
@italian seasoning{1%tbsp}, remaining stock concentrates, half the parsley,
@water{2/3%cup} (1 cup for 8 servings), @sugar{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 8),
salt, and pepper.

Bring to a simmer, stirring occasionally. Once simmering, add
@Israeli couscous{5%ounce}, cover, and reduce heat to low. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Transfer cooked couscous mixture to bowl with beef mixture. Add half the
remaining parsley and stir until thoroughly combined.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Once bell pepper halves are done roasting, remove sheet from oven. Heat broiler
to high.

Carefully transfer bell pepper halves to a work surface. Flip and stuff each
half with beef and couscous mixture. Sprinkle with @mozzarella cheese{1/2%cup}.

Return stuffed peppers to baking sheet (careful—baking sheet will still be hot!)
and broil until cheese is melted and bubbly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Keep a close eye on the peppers since the cheese can burn quickly!

Divide stuffed peppers between plates. Sprinkle with remaining parsley and serve.

> Ground beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.